Project Overview: Cost-Effective Alternative Catalysts for Industrial HydrogenationThis project was developed for Problem Statement 2 of the KINEXUS'25 Inter IIT NIT Hackathon in collaboration with Godrej Industries. It focuses on replacing traditional Nickel catalysts with a high-efficiency Supported Copper Catalyst ($Cu/SiO_2$) for the industrial hydrogenation of vegetable oils.Core ObjectivesCost Reduction: Utilize copper, which is cheaper and more abundant than nickel, eliminating the need for expensive additives or alloying.Enhanced Selectivity: Achieve precise partial hydrogenation to eliminate unstable trienic components (C18:3) while preserving desirable oleic acid (C18:1), effectively preventing over-saturation into stearic acid (C18:0).Environmental Sustainability: Implement a chromium-free, non-pyrophoric system that reduces metal loading from the 22 wt.% typically found in commercial Nickel to 8 wt.% Copper, significantly lowering hazardous waste generation per metric ton.Technical InnovationThe solution utilizes the Chemisorption-Hydrolysis (CH) method for catalyst preparation, as detailed in research by Ravasio et al. (2002):Morphology: Creates 3.5 nm copper nanoparticles with "step and edge" sites that are up to 100 times more active for hydrogen dissociation than traditional catalysts.Stability: Employs an ex situ pre-reduction treatment at $270^{\circ}C$ to remove all water formed during synthesis, preventing catalyst deactivation and ensuring long-term industrial robustness.Process DesignThe proposed system operates as a slurry-phase batch reactor. Crude vegetable oil undergoes degumming and bleaching before reacting with high-purity hydrogen gas at $150-220^{\circ}C$ and a pressure of 20 bar. This process ensures superior cold-flow properties, maintaining oil fluidity down to $-15^{\circ}C$, which is ideal for biodegradable lubricants and biodiesel.Research FoundationThe project is grounded in industrial benchmarking and academic research from Applied Catalysis A: General, specifically focusing on producing environmentally friendly lubricants with high oxidation stability
